n and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Tanner   2.","English: status name from Old French <i>teneor</i>, <i>teneur</i>, <i>tenor</i> ‘tenant’, for someone who held property from a lord by feudal service, hence an equivalent of   Tennant  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Tann","meanings":["German: topographic name for someone who lived in a forest, Middle High German <i>tan</i>. This was originally a distinct word from <i>tanne</i> ‘pine tree’, and denoted a forest of any kind. Inevitably, however, the two became confused, with the result that <i>Tann</i> now denotes only coniferous forests; in this form it is a rather rare and literary word.","English (mainly Norfolk): metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>tan(ne)</i> ‘oak bark’ (Old French <i>tan</i>), i.e. crushed oak bark used in tanning. See also   Tanner  .","English (mainly Norfolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Tan</i>, a pet form of   Andrew  . Compare   Tandy  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. John Tanner had at least 1 son with John Tanner."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1501–1560":"1501–1560","–Female":"Surnud","1501":"1501","1560":"1560","England":"England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1501–1560":"1501–1560","–Female":"Kuollut","1501":"1501","1560":"1560","England":"England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1501–1560":"1501–1560","–Female":"Décédée","1501":"1501","1560":"1560","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. John Tanner a eu au moins 1 fils avec John Tanner."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","–Male":"Verstorben","1501–1560":"1501–1560","–Female":"Verstorben","1501":"1501","1560":"1560","England":"England","lifeSummary":"Mrs. John Tanner hatte mit John Tanner mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"–":"Desede","–Male":"Desede","1501–1560":"1501–1560","–Female":"Desede","1501":"1501","1560":"15